<font color="#FF0000">TO JOE BUCKLEY</font><br>
<tt>Wed May 28 23:38:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Joe Buckley:<br><br>
Last year my younger daughter gave me a present for father's day. It was a large picture of the Wall. A middle aged man leans forward against the Wall in an expression of emotional pain. His buddies, and perhaps himself, stare back transparently through the reflection.<br><br>
My daughter was very proud of her gift. She said it was me!<br>
My family and I shared a two hour cry. I have it hung in the house, and I reflect upon it every day. Isn't it funny how kids know more than we ourselves sometimes realize.<br><br>
I have been to the Wall twice these past two years. I had been unable to visit the Wall until then. I wrote down my feelings on both visits. I will share them with everyone here in a few days.<br><br>
Going to the Wall continues to be the most difficult thing I have done in life, but the second time it was different, more peaceful. The can of beer in the zip loc bag given by a buddy standing next to me was all that it took to break me down into tears. Tears of pain, tears of joy. It is all there to experience.<br><br>
I know I must continue my visits to heal, to come to peace with my ghosts in the Wall. I know I can do it for them as well as me. I have survived, and will continue.<br><br>
Joe, when you are ready, go to the Wall with your family or a close personal friend. Its OK to cry and to feel. What we experienced in Vietnam was real, and this is no less.<br><br>
Peace, and my thoughts go with you. 
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


